The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, August 20, 2004 				 Shoppers Stop seeks IPO go-ahead 
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 				 	 Share the moolah																								Mumbai, Aug. 19: C. L. Raheja group-promoted Shoppers Stop Ltd today filed a red herring prospectus with the Securities and Exchange Board of India for its initial public offer.																								The company will issue 6,94,033 shares with a face value of Rs 10 each, constituting 20.21 per cent of the fully diluted post-issue paid-up capital. The issue will be a book-built one.																								Shoppers Stop will use the proceeds from the IPO to set up new stores and expand and renovate existing ones.																								The lead managers to the issue are Enam Financial Consultants, J M Morgan Stanley, Kotak Mahindra Capital and ICICI Securities. 																								After it gets listed, Shoppers Stop will join other retailing majors like Pantaloon, Trent, SB amp;T International on the bourses.																								Market circles said the issue comes at the right time after the successful initial public offering of Tata Consultancy Services. Moreover, the refunds from the TCS issue are also coming in.																								Shoppers Stops business has grown from a single store in Mumbai to 15, spread over cities like Mumbai, Delhi, Calcutta, Chennai, Bangalore, Hyderabad, Pune, Jaipur and Gurgaon.																								The first store was set up in 1991 and occupied an area of 2,800 sq ft. Now all Shoppers Stop stores together occupy an aggregate area of 687250 sq ft. 																								Shoppers Stop is a major player in the domestic retail sector and is a pioneer in the large-format department stores in the country. 																								The chain sells most leading Indian and international brands of garments and accessories.																								The company has six stores in Mumbai, one each in Delhi, Bangalore, Hyderabad, Jaipur, Pune, Gurgaon and Chennai, and two in Calcutta. Shoppers Stop is Indias largest retail chain of department stores. 																								It is also the only Indian member of the Intercontinental Group of Departmental stores along with 29 other experienced retailers from all over the world, including Selfridges of England, Karstadt of Germany, Takashimaya of Japan, C K Tang (Singapore) and Lamcy Plaza of Dubai.
